th=3D"605" data-file-height=3D"489"></a><figcaption>Farm-derived units of m=
easurement:<ol> <li>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)=
" title=3D"Rod (unit)">rod</a> is a historical unit of length equal to <lin=
k rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154=
941027"><span class=3D"frac">5<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=
=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span> yards.  It ma=
y have originated from the typical length of a mediaeval <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Goad" title=3D"Goad">ox-goad</a>. There are 4 rods i=
n one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)" title=3D"Chain=
 (unit)">chain</a>.</li> <li>The <a class=3D"mw-selflink selflink">furlong<=
/a> (meaning furrow length) was the distance a team of oxen could plough wi=
thout resting.  This was standardised to be exactly 40 rods or 10 chains.</=
li> <li>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre" title=3D"Acre">ac=
re</a> was the amount of land tillable by one man behind one team of eight =
oxen in one day.  Traditional acres were long and narrow due to the difficu=
lty in turning the plough and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Ribbon_farm" title=3D"Ribbon farm">value of river front access</a>.</li> <l=
i>An <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxgang" title=3D"Oxgang">oxga=
ng</a> was the amount of land tillable by one ox in a ploughing season.  Th=
is could vary from village to village, but was typically around 15 acres.</=
li> <li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Virgate" title=3D"Virgat=
e">virgate</a> was the amount of land tillable by two oxen in a ploughing s=
eason.</li> <li>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carucate" title=
=3D"Carucate">carucate</a> was the amount of land tillable by a team of eig=
ht oxen in a ploughing season.  This was equal to 8 oxgangs or 4 virgates.<=
/li> </ol> </figcaption></figure>
<p>A <b>furlong</b> is a measure of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Distance" title=3D"Distance">distance</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Imperial_units" title=3D"Imperial units">imperial units</a> an=
d <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_customary_units" t=
itle=3D"United States customary units">United States customary units</a> eq=
ual to one-eighth of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile" title=
=3D"Mile">mile</a>, equivalent to any of 660&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(unit)" title=3D"Foot (unit)">feet</a>, 220&nbsp;<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard" title=3D"Yard">yards</a>, 40&nbsp=
;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_(unit)" title=3D"Rod (unit)">=
rods or perches</a>, 10&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain=
_(unit)" title=3D"Chain (unit)">chains</a>, or approximately 201&nbsp;<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">metres</a>. It i=
s now mostly confined to use in horse racing, where in many countries<sup c=
lass=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Avoid_weasel_words" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Wikipedia:Avoid weasel words"><span title=3D"The materi=
al near this tag possibly uses too vague attribution or weasel words. (Sept=
ember 2024)">which?</span></a></i>]</sup> it is the standard measurement of=
 race lengths, and agriculture, where it is used to measure rural field len=
gths and distances.=20
</p><p>In the United States, some states use older definitions for surveyin=
g purposes, leading to variations in the length of the furlong of two parts=
 per million, or about <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"m=
w-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027">0.4 millimetres (<span class=3D"frac"><s=
pan class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">64</span></span> inc=
h). This variation is small enough to not have practical consequences in mo=
st applications.=20
</p><p>Using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_yar=
d_and_pound" title=3D"International yard and pound">international definitio=
n of the yard</a> as exactly 0.9144&nbsp;metres, one furlong is 201.168&nbs=
p;metres, and five furlongs are about 1&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Kilometre" title=3D"Kilometre">kilometre</a> (<link rel=3D"mw-de=
duplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027">1.0058=
4&nbsp;km exactly).
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFurlong&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span></a><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The name <i>furlong</i> derives from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Old_English" title=3D"Old English">Old English</a> words <i><span=
 title=3D"Old English (ca. 450-1100)-language text"><i lang=3D"ang">furh</i=
></span></i> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furrow" class=3D"mw-=
redirect" title=3D"Furrow">furrow</a>) and <i><span title=3D"Old English (c=
a. 450-1100)-language text"><i lang=3D"ang">lang</i></span></i> (long).<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Furlong#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Dating back at least to early <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anglo-Saxon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Anglo-Saxon">Anglo-Saxon</a> times, it originally referred to the lengt=
h of the furrow in one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acre" title=
=3D"Acre">acre</a> of a ploughed <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O=
pen-field_system" title=3D"Open-field system">open field</a> (a medieval co=
mmunal field which was divided into strips). The furlong (meaning furrow le=
ngth) was the distance a team of oxen could plough without resting. This wa=
s standardised to be exactly 40&nbsp;rods or 10&nbsp;chains. The system of =
long furrows arose because turning a team of oxen pulling a heavy plough wa=
s difficult. This offset the drainage advantages of short furrows and meant=
 furrows were made as long as possible. An acre is an area that is one furl=
ong long and one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)" tit=
le=3D"Chain (unit)">chain</a> (66&nbsp;feet or 22&nbsp;yards) wide. For thi=
s reason, the furlong was once also called an <b>acre's length</b>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Furlong#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> though in modern usage an area of one acr=
e can be of any shape. The term furlong, or shot, was also used to describe=
 a grouping of adjacent strips within an open field.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_n=
ote-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Among the early Anglo-Saxons, the rod was the fundamental unit of la=
nd measurement. A furlong was 40&nbsp;rods; an acre 4 by 40&nbsp;rods, or 4=
&nbsp;rods by 1&nbsp;furlong, and thus 160&nbsp;square rods; there are 10&n=
bsp;acres in a square furlong. At the time, the Saxons used the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(unit)#England" title=3D"Foot (unit)">No=
rth German foot</a>, which was about 10&nbsp;percent longer than the foot o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/International_yard_and_pound=
" title=3D"International yard and pound">international 1959 agreement</a>. =
When England <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_of_Yards_=
and_Perches" title=3D"Composition of Yards and Perches">changed to a shorte=
r foot</a> in the late 13th&nbsp;century, rods and furlongs remained unchan=
ged, since property boundaries were already defined in rods and furlongs. T=
he only thing that changed was the number of feet and yards in a rod or a f=
urlong, and the number of square feet and square yards in an acre. The defi=
nition of the rod went from 15&nbsp;old feet to <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicate=
d-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"=
frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=
=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>&nbsp;new feet, or from 5&nbsp;old ya=
rds to <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateS=
tyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">5<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><s=
pan class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>&nbsp=
;new yards. The furlong went from 600 old feet to 660 new feet, or from 200=
&nbsp;old yards to 220&nbsp;new yards. The acre went from 36,000&nbsp;old s=
quare feet to 43,560&nbsp;new square feet, or from 4,000&nbsp;old square ya=
rds to 4,840&nbsp;new square yards.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-4"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 =20
</p><p>The furlong was historically viewed as being equivalent to the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stadion_(unit)" title=3D"Stadion (unit)=
">Roman stade (<i>stadium</i>)</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-5"><span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 which in turn derived from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/An=
cient_Greek_units_of_measurement" title=3D"Ancient Greek units of measureme=
nt">Greek system</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" s=
tyle=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/W=
ikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=
=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2025)">citatio=
n needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>In the Roman system, there were 625&nbsp;feet to the <i>stadium</i>,=
 eight <i>stadia</i> to the mile, and 1=C2=BD&nbsp;miles to the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/League_(unit)" title=3D"League (unit)">league=
</a>. A league was considered to be the distance a man could walk in one ho=
ur, and the mile (from <i>mille</i>, meaning "thousand") consisted of 1,000=
&nbsp;<i>passus</i> (paces, five&nbsp;feet, or double-step).<sup class=3D"n=
oprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"W=
ikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to rel=
iable sources. (August 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>After the fall of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weste=
rn_Roman_Empire" title=3D"Western Roman Empire">Western Roman Empire</a>, m=
edieval Europe continued with the Roman system, which the people proceeded =
to diversify, leading to serious complications in trade, taxation, etc.<sup=
 class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:No_original_research" title=3D=
"Wikipedia:No original research"><span title=3D"The material near this tag =
possibly contains original research. (August 2025)">original research?</spa=
n></a></i>]</sup> Around the year 1300, by royal decree, England standardiz=
ed a long list of measures.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-F=
act" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span t=
itle=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2025)">cit=
ation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> Among the important units of distance an=
d length at the time were the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot=
_(unit)" title=3D"Foot (unit)">foot</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Yard" title=3D"Yard">yard</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Rod_(unit)" title=3D"Rod (unit)">rod</a> (or pole), furlong, and the <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile" title=3D"Mile">mile</a>. The r=
od was defined as <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-dat=
a:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">5<span class=3D"sr-only"=
>+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span><=
/span>&nbsp;yards or <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-=
data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-o=
nly">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</sp=
an></span>&nbsp;feet, and the mile was eight furlongs, so the definition of=
 the furlong became 40&nbsp;rods and that of the mile became 5,280&nbsp;fee=
t (eight furlongs/mile times 40&nbsp;rods/furlong times <link rel=3D"mw-ded=
uplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1154941027"><span c=
lass=3D"frac">16<span class=3D"sr-only">+</span><span class=3D"num">1</span=
>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">2</span></span>&nbsp;feet/rod). The invention=
 of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunter%27s_chain" title=3D=
"Gunter's chain">measuring chain</a> in the 1620s led to the introduction o=
f an intermediate unit of length, the chain of 22&nbsp;yards, being equal t=
o four rods, and to one-tenth of a furlong.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Tem=
plate Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation=
 needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (A=
ugust 2025)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>A description from 1675 states, "Dimensurator or Measuring Instrumen=
t whereof the mosts usual has been the Chain, and the common length for Eng=
lish Measures four Poles, as answering indifferently to the Englishs Mile a=
nd Acre, 10 such Chains in length making a Furlong, and 10 single square Ch=
ains an Acre, so that a square Mile contains 640&nbsp;square Acres."<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-ogleby1670_6-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-ogleby1670-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The official use of the furlong was abolished in the United Kingdom =
under the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weights_and_Measures_Act=
s_(UK)" title=3D"Weights and Measures Acts (UK)">Weights and Measures Act</=
a> 1985, an act that also abolished the official use of many other traditio=
nal units of measurement.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fac=
t" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span tit=
le=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (August 2025)">citat=
ion needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Use">Use</h2><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DFurlong&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;=
section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Use"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Milepost_358-6_on_Yangon-Mand=
alay_Expressway.JPG" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uplo=
ad.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/b/b8/Milepost_358-6_on_Yangon-Mand=
alay_Expressway.JPG/250px-Milepost_358-6_on_Yangon-Mandalay_Expressway.JPG"=
 decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"177" class=3D"mw-file-element" =
data-file-width=3D"1000" data-file-height=3D"706"></a><figcaption>Mileposts=
 on the Yangon=E2=80=93Mandalay Expressway use miles followed by furlongs (=
this sign has numbers that do not reflect these measurements)</figcaption><=
/figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Myanmar" title=3D"Myanmar">M=
yanmar</a> furlongs are currently used in conjunction with miles to indicat=
e distances on highway signs. Mileposts on the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Yangon%E2%80%93Mandalay_Expressway" title=3D"Yangon=E2=80=93Ma=
ndalay Expressway">Yangon=E2=80=93Mandalay Expressway</a> use miles and fur=
longs.
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:036175_5_furlong.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/f/fb/036175_5_furlong.jpg/250px-036175_5_furlong.jpg" decodi=
ng=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"188" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-fi=
le-width=3D"1024" data-file-height=3D"768"></a><figcaption>The five-furlong=
 (1000&nbsp;m) post on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epsom_Downs=
_Racecourse" title=3D"Epsom Downs Racecourse">Epsom Downs Racecourse</a></f=
igcaption></figure>
<p>In the rest of the world the furlong has very limited use, with the nota=
ble exception of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horse_racing" tit=
le=3D"Horse racing">horse racing</a> in most English-speaking countries, in=
cluding Canada and the United States. The distances for <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horse_racing#Australia" title=3D"Horse racing">horse =
racing</a> in Australia were converted to metric in 1972<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-7" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#ci=
te_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> and the term survives only in slang.<sup class=3D"nop=
rint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wik=
ipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to relia=
ble sources. (October 2024)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> In the U=
nited Kingdom,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Ireland, Canada, and=
 the United States, races are still given in miles and furlongs. Also dista=
nces along English canals navigated by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Narrowboat" title=3D"Narrowboat">narrowboats</a> are commonly expresse=
d in miles and furlongs.
</p><p>The city of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roads_and_expre=
ssways_in_Chicago" title=3D"Roads and expressways in Chicago">Chicago's str=
eet numbering system</a> allots a measure of 800 address units to each mile=
, in keeping with the city's system of eight blocks per mile. This means th=
at every block in a typical Chicago neighborhood (in either north=E2=80=93s=
outh or east=E2=80=93west direction but rarely both) is approximately one f=
urlong in length. City blocks in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Hoddle_Grid" title=3D"Hoddle Grid">Hoddle Grid</a> of <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Melbourne" title=3D"Melbourne">Melbourne</a> are als=
o one furlong in length. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Salt_Lake=
_City" title=3D"Salt Lake City">Salt Lake City</a>'s blocks are each a squa=
re furlong in the downtown area. The blocks become less regular in shape fa=
rther from the center, but the numbering system (800&nbsp;units to each mil=
e) remains the same everywhere in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Salt_Lake_County,_Utah" title=3D"Salt Lake County, Utah">Salt Lake County</=
a>. Blocks in central <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Logan,_Utah"=
 title=3D"Logan, Utah">Logan, Utah</a>, and in large sections of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phoenix,_Arizona" title=3D"Phoenix, Arizona"=
>Phoenix, Arizona</a>, are similarly a square furlong in extent (eight to a=
 mile, which explains the series of freeway exits: 19th Ave, 27th, 35th, 43=
rd, 51st, 59th&nbsp;...).=20
</p><p>Much of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ontario" title=3D"O=
ntario">Ontario</a>, Canada, was originally surveyed on a ten-furlong grid,=
 with major roads being laid out along the grid lines. Now that distances a=
re shown on road signs in kilometres, these major roads are almost exactly =
two kilometres apart. The exits on highways running through <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Toronto" title=3D"Toronto">Toronto</a>, for examp=
le, are generally at intervals of two kilometres.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note=
-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bangor_City_Forest" tit=
le=3D"Bangor City Forest">Bangor City Forest</a> in Bangor, Maine has its t=
rail system marked in miles and furlongs.
</p><p>The furlong is also a base unit of the humorous <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/FFF_system" title=3D"FFF system">FFF system</a> of uni=
ts.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-SKB_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-SKB-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition_of_length">Defin=
ition of length</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DFurlong&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Defin=
ition of length"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>The exact length of the furlong varies slightly among English-speaking c=
ountries. In Canada<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and the Unit=
ed Kingdom,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which define the fur=
long in terms of the international yard of exactly 0.9144&nbsp;metres, a fu=
rlong is 201.168&nbsp;m. Australia<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-14"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> does not formally define the furlong, but it does define the chain and l=
ink in terms of the international yard.
</p><p>The United States previously defined the furlong, chain, rod, and <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link_(unit)" title=3D"Link (unit)">l=
ink</a> in terms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._surve=
y_foot" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"U.S. survey foot">U.S. survey foot</=
a> of exactly <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:Te=
mplateStyles:r1154941027"><span class=3D"frac"><span class=3D"num">1200</sp=
an>=E2=81=84<span class=3D"den">3937</span></span>&nbsp;metre,<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fur=
long#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> resulting in a furlong approximately 201.168=
4&nbsp;m long. The difference of approximately two parts per million betwee=
n the old U.S. value and the "international" value was insignificant for mo=
st practical measurements.
</p><p>In October 2019, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U.S._Natio=
nal_Geodetic_Survey" title=3D"U.S. National Geodetic Survey">U.S. National =
Geodetic Survey</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_I=
nstitute_of_Standards_and_Technology" title=3D"National Institute of Standa=
rds and Technology">National Institute of Standards and Technology</a> anno=
unced their joint intent to retire the U.S. survey foot, with effect from t=
he end of 2022. The furlong in U.S. Customary units is thereafter defined b=
ased on the International 1959 foot, giving the length of the furlong as ex=
act 201.168&nbsp;meters in the United States as well.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite=
_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
